What the publish flag actually does under the hood.

When you publish a port, the daemon does two things behind the scenes, and knowing both makes networking problems much easier to debug.

The first is a firewall translation rule. On linux, docker inserts a rule that rewrites incoming traffic destined for the host port into traffic destined for the container's eye-pee and port. This is the fast path, handled entirely in kernel space with no copying, and you can actually see these rules if you list the network-address-translation table. The second is a userland proxy as a fallback. For traffic that cannot go through that firewall rule, such as some local-host-to-local-host cases, the daemon runs a small helper process that listens on the host port and forwards to the container. This is the slow path, costing a system-call round-trip per packet, and you can disable it in the daemon configuration if you want pure firewall-rule handling, though most teams leave it on.

Why does this matter to you. For performance, heavy network workloads should at least measure the impact, though for most apps the cost is invisible. For visibility, when two things cannot talk over a published port, those firewall rules are the prime suspect, and listing them is your debugging tool. There is also the classic cannot-bind-that-port error, which simply means something on the host is already listening there, so you pick a different host port. And remember that on mac and windows there is no real firewall chain on your machine at all. Docker desktop emulates port publishing inside its virtual machine, so it is the same flag with a different mechanism underneath.
